<section class="section-text strip-line none no-illo strip-top">

    

    <div class="content-wrapper">

      

        <div class="sect-title-wrapper">
          <h2 class="sect-title">First Steps</h2>
          <div class="underline"></div>
        </div>

      
  
      <div class="text-wrapper">    
        
        
          <p><span class="smallest stretch-cap">By Scott Bedford, Illustrator, Author</span></p>
        

        
        
          <p>I have drawn machines, contraptions and gadgets for as long as I can remember. As a child, the Wacky Races and Catch the Pigeon cartoons left a lasting impression, not because of Dick Dastardly and Mutley, as iconic as they were, but for the crazy, imaginative, wacky, cars and aeroplanes.</p>
        

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         


         

         

      </div>

      <div class="bg-texture-wrapper">
        <div class="frame show"><div class="top-frame"></div><div class="bottom-frame"></div></div>
        <div class="bg-texture"></div>
      </div>

    </div>
    
</section>

<!-- SECTION TEXT -->

<section class="section-text strip-line blue">

    
      <div class="sect-illo-wrapper pipe-gauge"><div class="sect-illo"></div></div>
    

    <div class="content-wrapper">

      

        <div class="sect-title-wrapper">
          <h2 class="sect-title">Early Accolades</h2>
          <div class="underline"></div>
        </div>

      
  
      <div class="text-wrapper">    
        
        
          <p>Aged 8, I entered a national art competition sponsoured by Kraft cheeses. I won my age category with an inventive drawing of a cheese factory, boasting a Rude Goldberg style production line. My prize? To visit children's TV art icon, Tony Hart, at the BBC's Bristol studios.</p>
        

        
        

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         


         

         

      </div>

      <div class="bg-texture-wrapper">
        <div class="frame show"><div class="top-frame"></div><div class="bottom-frame"></div></div>
        <div class="bg-texture"></div>
      </div>

    </div>
    
</section>

<!-- SECTION TEXT -->

<section class="section-text strip-line none">

    
      <div class="sect-illo-wrapper pipe-plain"><div class="sect-illo"></div></div>
    

    <div class="content-wrapper">

      

        <div class="sect-title-wrapper">
          <h2 class="sect-title">Professional Validation</h2>
          <div class="underline"></div>
        </div>

      
  
      <div class="text-wrapper">    
        
        
          <p>Fast forward to 2011. My illustration 'How Tweets are Made' was selected for inclusion in the presticious Creative Review Illustration Annual. This was proof that my inventive illustrations could find a home... if they could stir judges, they could stir consumers, customers and clients.</p>
        

        
        

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         


         

         

      </div>

      <div class="bg-texture-wrapper">
        <div class="frame show"><div class="top-frame"></div><div class="bottom-frame"></div></div>
        <div class="bg-texture"></div>
      </div>

    </div>
    
</section>

<!-- SECTION TEXT -->

<section class="section-text strip-line blue join">

    
      <div class="sect-illo-wrapper pipe-whistle"><div class="sect-illo"></div></div>
    

    <div class="content-wrapper">

      

        <div class="sect-title-wrapper">
          <h2 class="sect-title">Final Catalyst</h2>
          <div class="underline"></div>
        </div>

      
  
      <div class="text-wrapper">    
        
        
          <p>Although I went on to author and illustrate <a href="/books">three books</a>, including a best-selling craft book, it was a hand drawn PowerPoint template (full of my inventive illustrations) that was the final catalyst, not because it sold so well, but because of the priceless customer feedback.</p>
        

        
        

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         

        
         


         

         

      </div>

